"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983217","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-16","<p>​​The British Embassy in Ankara has engaged with the Turkish authorities about returning Anna Campbell's body to her family and with the International Red Cross. Due to the situation on the ground it is extremely difficult to confirm the whereabouts of any British nationals in Syria. We continue to stress to Turkey the importance of ensuring that the UN and non-governmental organisation partners are able to operate in areas under Turkish control. We stand ready to engage further with the authorities should the situation change.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-10-16T15:01:55.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983217/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983217/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-08","Anna Campbell","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations has he made to the Turkish Government on the repatriation of the body of British national Anna Campbell from that country.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","176250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983218","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-10-16","<p>The Commission’s proposal does not present a strong evidence base that shows why the change is necessary nor that demonstrates the benefits to Member States, their citizens, or the EU.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2018-10-16T16:24:21.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983218/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983218/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-08","Summertime: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of European Commission proposals to change EU summertime arrangements on Government policy, in the event that the UK leaves the EU in March 2019.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","176024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983219","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-11","<p>​The principles of the 2010 Protection of Civilians Strategy, continues to guide our work and we consistently review our cross-Government approach. We aim to address the growing challenges of protecting civilians affected by conflict through political engagement, strengthening accountability, peace support operations, ensuring respect for International Humanitarian Law in UK military operations, strengthening state and non-state capacity, humanitarian action, and offering refuge to those in need of protection. The continuing evolution of our approach is demonstrated by the UK's adherence, in April 2018, to the Safe Schools Declaration which supports the protection and continuation of education in armed conflict.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-10-11T10:39:29.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983219/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983219/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-08","Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to update the protection of civilians strategy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","176616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983220","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-16","<p>The Secretary of State for Health and Social Care regularly speaks to the Chancellor of the Exchequer on a range of issues. The Department does not hold a record of a discussion between the current Secretary of State and the Chancellor of the Exchequer on this specific issue.</p><p>Officials from the Department of Health and Social Care have regular discussions with officials from the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport to review the implementation of Sporting Futures Strategy. Discussions include reviewing programmes to embed physical activity into care pathways and raising awareness of the United Kingdom Chief Medical Officers’ physical activity guidelines.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","176091","2018-10-16T16:23:15.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983220/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983220/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-08","Exercise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the cost to the public purse of embedding physical activity into care pathways as recommended by the sporting future strategy 2015.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","176090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983221","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-16","<p>The Secretary of State for Health and Social Care regularly speaks to the Chancellor of the Exchequer on a range of issues. The Department does not hold a record of a discussion between the current Secretary of State and the Chancellor of the Exchequer on this specific issue.</p><p>Officials from the Department of Health and Social Care have regular discussions with officials from the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport to review the implementation of Sporting Futures Strategy. Discussions include reviewing programmes to embed physical activity into care pathways and raising awareness of the United Kingdom Chief Medical Officers’ physical activity guidelines.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","176090","2018-10-16T16:23:15.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983221/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983221/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-08","Exercise: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the cost to the public purse of encouraging children to be physically active in their early years as set out in the sporting future strategy 2015.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","176091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983222","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-10-16","<p>An inclusive and professional sport and physical activity workforce is a vital part of the sport and physical activity strategies of both government and the national sport council, Sport England.</p><p> </p><p>Sport England published its workforce strategy ‘Working in an Active Nation’ on 12 September 2018 after a widespread sector consultation. The strategy sets out the intention to support the sport and physical activity workforce to become more customer focused and to increase its recognition as a professional sector.</p><p> </p><p>Sport England has developed a series of strategic approaches and key actions that will help achieve the strategy’s objectives. This includes engaging with both traditional and new partners across the sector to improve the diversity and inclusion of the workforce at all levels.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-10-16T15:59:00.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983222/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983222/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-10-08","Exercise: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has in place to encourage (a) over-55s to become fitness instructors and coaches (b) other aspects of diversity in the physical activity sector workforce.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","176092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983223","Treasury","false","2018-10-12","<p>This Government is committed to supporting families and we will be spending around £6 billion every year by 2020 on childcare support – more than ever before.</p><p> </p><p>A marketing campaign was launched in September to increase awareness and take-up of Tax-Free Childcare. Parents can use their Tax-Free Childcare account to pay for childcare at any Ofsted registered provider, including out of school activities and holiday clubs.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-10-12T10:15:50.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983223/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983223/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-08","Extracurricular Activities: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will use underspending on tax-free childcare to fund out-of-school activities and holiday engagement programmes in disadvantaged areas.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","176093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983224","Department for Education","false","2018-10-16","<p>New multi-agency arrangements were introduced through the Children and Social Work Act 2017, which set the framework for how the three safeguarding partners (police, health and local authorities) should work with other key agencies, including schools, to safeguard and promote the welfare of children in their area.</p><p>Once designated as a relevant agency by the safeguarding partners, schools must comply with their local arrangements. Beyond this, it is up to schools to decide how best to operate in practice with health and social care services to provide support for pupils and their families and engage with the community more widely.</p><p>The Government recognises that schools are well placed to act as a focus for collaborative delivery of early intervention services, an important part of maintaining children and young people’s engagement in education.</p><p>An example of this will be the introduction of new mental health support teams as part of the proposals set out in the 'Transforming Children and Young People’s Mental Health Services' green paper. These teams will work collaboratively across schools, colleges and NHS mental health services to support children with emerging and moderate mental health issues and to boost preventative activity. The intention is that teams should work with other existing local authority, health and voluntary and community sector provision to ensure that children and young people receive the right support at the right time.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-10-16T16:34:55.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983224/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983224/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-08","Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether he plans to promote the school-as-community-hub model with integrated health, education and social care provision for children and family engagement outside the school day; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","176094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983225","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-15","<p>The Government is committed to offering greater protection to tenants and ensuring that people are living in safe and good quality properties.</p><p>The majority of landlords already take the safety of their tenants seriously. Landlords have their electrical installations checked regularly to identify and eliminate possible hazards unseen by the tenant. Existing legislation already requires landlords to keep electrical installations in their property in repair and proper working order and it is currently best practice for landlords to organise periodic inspection and testing and to provide a report to the tenant.</p><p>On 19 July 2018, we announced that we will introduce a mandatory requirement on landlords in the private rented sector to ensure electrical installations in their property are inspected every five years. We are working to bring these regulations into force as soon as possible, subject to parliamentary approval and timetable.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","175884","2018-10-15T16:05:58.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983225/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983225/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-08","Private Rented Housing: Electrical Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent progress his Department has made on introducing mandatory electrical safety checks in the private rented sector; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","175881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983226","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-16","<p>The Government has recently announced that it will introduce new requirements for landlords to conduct electrical safety checks in the private rented sector to help ensure the safety of all their tenants, including older people. In the Social Housing Green Paper we are consulting on whether new safety measures in the private rented sector should also apply to social housing, as well as whether there are any changes needed to the definition of what constitutes a Decent Home<em>. </em></p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-10-16T14:58:11.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983226/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983226/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-08","Electrical Safety: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of introducing free electrical safety checks for vulnerable older people.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","175882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983227","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-16","<p>The Department does not run any schemes to provide financial support for electrical safety remedial work in the owner occupied sector.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-10-16T14:57:36.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983227/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983227/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-08","Owner Occupation: Electrical Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what help is available to people living in the owner-occupied housing sector who have electrically unsafe properties but are unable to afford essential remedial work.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","175883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983228","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-15","<p>The Government is committed to offering greater protection to tenants and ensuring that people are living in safe and good quality properties.</p><p>The majority of landlords already take the safety of their tenants seriously. Landlords have their electrical installations checked regularly to identify and eliminate possible hazards unseen by the tenant. Existing legislation already requires landlords to keep electrical installations in their property in repair and proper working order and it is currently best practice for landlords to organise periodic inspection and testing and to provide a report to the tenant.</p><p>On 19 July 2018, we announced that we will introduce a mandatory requirement on landlords in the private rented sector to ensure electrical installations in their property are inspected every five years. We are working to bring these regulations into force as soon as possible, subject to parliamentary approval and timetable.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","175881","2018-10-15T16:05:58.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983228/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983228/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-08","Private Rented Housing: Electrical Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential merits of preventing landlords from letting properties that are electrically unsafe.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","175884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983229","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-11","<p>The Ministry of Defence’s consultancy expenditure for 2017-18 by supplier rounded to the nearest £1,000 is published online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/mod-spending-over-25000-january-to-december-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/mod-spending-over-25000-january-to-december-2018</a></p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2018-10-11T15:28:47.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983229/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/983229/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-08","Ministry of Defence: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to page 14 of the Finance & Economics Annual Bulletin Departmental Resources Statistics 2018, if he will publish the companies his Department has contracted for consultancy and how much of the £50 million consultancy spend was spent with each company.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","176133"
