"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973220","Treasury","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Government is considering the responses to the consultation on non-compliance with the off-payroll working rules in the private sector. A number of these responses were from individuals who identified themselves as self-employed.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will issue a formal response to the consultation in due course.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-10-09T14:42:04.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973220/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973220/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-13","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received from self-employed people on the potential extension of IR35 off-payroll tax to the private sector; and what proportion of those representations have been critical of that potential change.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","174787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973221","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-15","<p>Network Rail will save circa £18.1million annually, in operational costs of the Commercial Estate business.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-10-15T10:39:27.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973221/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973221/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-13","Network Rail: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate has been made of the potential annual savings that will accrue to Network Rail after the sale of its property portfolio to Telereal Trillium and Blackstone Property Partners.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","174778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973222","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-09","<p>Section 6 of the Health and safety at Work etc. Act 1974 places duties on any person who designs, manufacturers, imports or supplies any article for use at work to ensure that it will be safe and without risks to health. In general this applies to all devices used in the workplace but there are exceptions, such as medical devices, which are regulated by specific regulations that set out more detailed duties.</p><p> </p><p>The Medical Devices Regulations 2002 deal with the design, manufacture, import or supply of medical devices, including those which may contain computers/software. It is for the designer, manufacturer, importer or supplier to demonstrate that their product is safe. These regulations transpose the requirements of the following European Directives concerning product safety for medical devices:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Council Directive 90/385/EEC on Active Implantable Medical Devices (AIMDD)(1990)</li><li>Council Directive 93/42/EEC on Medical Devices (MDD)(1993)</li><li>Council Directive 98/79/EC on In Vitro Diagnostic Medical Devices (IVDMD)(1998)</li></ul><p>The Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Authority (MHRA) regulates medical devices in the UK. The following link provides more information on MHRA and its role:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/topic/medicines-medical-devices-blood/medical-devices-regulation-safety" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/topic/medicines-medical-devices-blood/medical-devices-regulation-safety</a>.</p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-10-09T11:12:31.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973222/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973222/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-13","Health and Safety at Work etc Act 1974 ","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether she has made an assessment of the effectiveness of section 6 of the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974 as it applies to medical devices containing computers; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","174600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973223","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-15","<p>The Last Mile Call for Evidence did not exclude HGVs. It sought ideas and evidence on ways of reducing emissions from the delivery of goods during the last mile of their journey, regardless of the size of vehicle used to deliver them.</p><p> </p><p>The Call for Evidence is also interested in a wide range of potential technologies for reducing emissions from last mile deliveries. This includes hybrid technologies for commercial vehicles, such as range-extended or dual-fuelled HGVs.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will be announcing its response to the call for evidence later this year.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","174780","2018-10-15T13:17:24.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973223/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973223/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-13","Large Goods Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reason his call for evidence on last-mile deliveries excludes HGVs.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","174779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973224","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-15","<p>The Last Mile Call for Evidence did not exclude HGVs. It sought ideas and evidence on ways of reducing emissions from the delivery of goods during the last mile of their journey, regardless of the size of vehicle used to deliver them.</p><p> </p><p>The Call for Evidence is also interested in a wide range of potential technologies for reducing emissions from last mile deliveries. This includes hybrid technologies for commercial vehicles, such as range-extended or dual-fuelled HGVs.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will be announcing its response to the call for evidence later this year.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","174779","2018-10-15T13:17:24.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973224/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973224/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-13","Large Goods Vehicles: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of the introduction of range-extended, dual-fuelled HGVs to reduce last-mile emissions in urban environments.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","174780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973225","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-09","<p>The recent consultation “Strengthening consumer redress in the housing market” sought views on how to ensure consumers have access to appropriate redress when things go wrong with their housing. This included considering whether bringing together redress schemes into a single housing ombudsman service could help simplify access.</p><p>We have been considering responses to the consultation and intend to publish our response later this year.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-10-09T15:12:15.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973225/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973225/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-09-13","Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, when he plans to publish his Department’s response to the consultation, Strengthening consumer redress in housing, which closed on 16 April 2018.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","174769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973226","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions does not hold data on the number of households in receipt of a free television license broken down by Parliamentary constituency.</p><p> </p><p>The number of households in receipt of winter fuel payment (aged 75 and over) by Parliamentary constituency can be used as a proxy for television license (assuming those in receipt of winter fuel payment have a television) and can be found in the dataset ‘Households by Parliamentary constituency and age, Winter Fuel Payment, 2017 to 2018 via the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/winter-fuel-payment-recipient-and-household-figures-2017-to-20178" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/winter-fuel-payment-recipient-and-household-figures-2017-to-20178</a></p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-10-09T10:57:23.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973226/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973226/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-13","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households occupied by at least one person over 75 were in receipt of a free television licence by constituency in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","174647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973227","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-15","<p>The purpose of the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency’s (DVLA) Vehicle Enquiry Service is to provide some details about the vehicle being checked, for example its licensing status.</p><p> </p><p>The DVLA already has existing secure data sharing arrangements in place which are used by the police and local authorities for enforcement purposes.</p><p> </p><p>If the registered keeper of a vehicle suspects that their number plate has been cloned, they should contact the police and the authority that issued any disputed penalty notice for investigations to be carried out. The DVLA is also able to issue a new registration number where appropriate.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-10-15T10:55:27.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973227/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973227/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-13","Vehicle Number Plates: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport,  what steps the Government is taking to encourage traffic enforcement teams to check with the DVLA vehicle enquiry service before issuing penalty notices in order to avoid problems caused by potential vehicle license plate cloning.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","174783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973228","Home Office","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Government remains committed to tackling harms caused by alcohol. Our new alcohol strategy will set out targeted action to prevent and reduce harmful drinking, support vulnerable people affected by others’ alcohol misuse and improve the pathways into treatment for people with alcohol dependency.</p><p>As we develop measures to include in the strategy, we are consulting widely across government and with a range of stakeholders including the health sector, academics, the voluntary sector and representatives of the alcohol industry and the licensed trade.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-10-09T15:58:47.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973228/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973228/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-13","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he will outline the scope of the consultation exercise to be undertaken in preparation for the forthcoming alcohol strategy.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","174683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973229","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-10","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) has been engaged in an ongoing process to ensure it has sufficient resource capability to deliver EU exit related work. Staff working in dedicated EU exit roles have principally been deployed from elsewhere in the DVLA or through wider Civil Service recruitment. Some DVLA staff are also working on EU exit related issues as part of their day to day roles, rather than being dedicated solely to EU exit work.</p><p> </p><p>Given the interactions between EU exit work and other priorities, the continuous review of business resourcing needs, and the adaptation of existing jobs, it is not possible to provide an estimate of the number of extra DVLA staff recruited to deal with EU exit related work.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2018-10-10T16:17:02.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973229/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973229/answer","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973229/answer/previousversion/77300","Biography information for Chris Grayling","27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-13","Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the additional staff required to work at the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency to cover work related to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","174684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973230","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-10","<p>There is currently no requirement for visitors to carry an International Driving Permit (IDP) to allow them to drive in the UK. After the UK leaves the EU, these arrangements are not expected to change. As a result, there will be no requirement to check IDPs for EU driving licence holders entering the UK.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2018-10-10T12:46:53.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973230/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973230/answer","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973230/answer/previousversion/77303","Biography information for Chris Grayling","27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-13","Driving: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the additional staff required to issue and check International Driver Permits for drivers entering the UK from the EU member states after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","174685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973231","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-15","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) is currently improving the way it holds data and the services it provides to customers. As part of this process the DVLA will provide a new service to notify changes of address covering both driver and vehicle databases. As most customers want to notify changes online, the DVLA will focus on delivering a digital service, with other support and assistance available for those who need it.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-10-15T13:05:49.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973231/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973231/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-13","Motor Vehicles: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the Government plans to introduce a combined form to enable people to notify the DVLA of a change of address for both driving licence and registered vehicle keeper.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","174784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973232","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-10","<p>The UK Government is not responsible for issuing International Driving Permits (IDPs) to driving licence holders from other EU Member States.</p><p> </p><p>While we are a member of the EU, UK driving licences continue to be recognised by all EU Member States, so IDPs are not required for UK licence holders.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is seeking to ensure that UK motorists can continue to drive in the EU after we have left. The treatment of driving licences will depend on the outcome of the final agreement.</p><p> </p><p>If there is no agreement with the EU, both private and professional drivers may need an IDP, as well as their UK driving licence, to drive in the EU following the UK’s exit.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2018-10-10T16:19:44.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973232/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973232/answer","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973232/answer/previousversion/77302","Biography information for Chris Grayling","27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-13","Driving: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many International Driver Permits have been issued to EU drivers and haulage companies in preparation for the UK leaving the EU to date.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","174686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973233","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-10-09","<p>Expenditure in the last five years was nil.</p><p> </p><p>Security personnel are not employed to assist with the administrative processing of tribunal cases; this is undertaken by dedicated administrative staff.</p><p> </p><p>Contracted security personnel are, however, deployed to ensure the security and safety of all persons who work in and attend tribunal premises, and undertake specific duties including searching the public on entry and responding to security incidents. They are not involved in any administrative process outside of those duties.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-10-09T16:18:37.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973233/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973233/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-09-13","HM Courts and Tribunals Service: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 11 September to Question 169517, how much his Department has spent on contracted security personnel to assist with the processing of tribunal cases in Scotland in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","174771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973234","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-10","<p>The UK does not currently require visitors to carry an International Driving Permit (IDP) to allow them to drive here. After the UK leaves the EU, arrangements for drivers who do not hold a UK driving licence who are visiting or living in the UK will not change. As a result, there will be no requirement to check IDPs for EU driving licence holders entering the UK.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2018-10-10T16:14:42.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973234/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973234/answer","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973234/answer/previousversion/77296","Biography information for Chris Grayling","27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-13","Driving: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of International Driver Permit checks that will be required for drivers who do not hold UK driving licenses who enter the UK from the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","174687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973235","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-15","<p>The Government is seeking to ensure that UK motorists can continue to drive in the EU after we have left. The treatment of driving licences will depend on the outcome of the final agreement.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>If there is no deal with the EU, both private and professional drivers may need an International Driving Permit, as well as their UK driving licence, to drive in the EU after the UK leaves.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-10-15T12:51:21.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973235/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973235/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-13","Driving: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether drivers of goods vehicles who hold UK driving licenses will be required to purchase an International Driving Permit to travel to EU member states after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","174688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973236","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-10-09","<p>The Uniformed Youth Fund will increase places in uniformed youth groups to reach disadvantaged young people. The Fund is open to uniformed youth organisations in England and is being managed by Youth United Foundation. The Fund is currently open for applications and will prioritise expansion in deprived areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-10-09T16:00:48.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973236/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973236/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-09-13","Children: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the announcement, Government invests £5m to increase places for disadvantaged children in youth organisations, published on 10 September 2018, to which areas he plans to distribute that funding; and whether he has plans to allocate funding from that fund to Wakefield.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","174651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973237","Department for International Trade","false","2018-10-15","<p>The UK and Israel have a strong and important trading relationship, and we are committed to strengthening it. The commercial team in our Embassy in Tel Aviv actively promote UK-Israel trade in the medical sector and are sponsoring a delegation of 6 Israeli importers of medical devices to meet with UK companies at the upcoming Medica Trade Exhibition this year.</p><p><br>There is also extensive bilateral collaborative medical research between the UK and Israel. The UK-Israel Tech Hub, based at the Embassy, helps to create tech and innovation partnerships across several sectors, including healthcare.</p><p><br>Next month, the Embassy is organising a visit by a delegation of senior NHS officials to Tel Aviv to meet with Israeli healthcare companies who are looking to invest in the UK.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2018-10-15T16:12:09.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973237/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973237/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-09-13","Overseas Trade: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to strengthen the collaboration between UK and Israeli companies in the medical sector.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","174724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973238","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-10-15","<p>The UK Government remains committed to the principles behind the Voisinage Agreement and to continued cooperation between Northern Ireland and Ireland. I wrote to Minister Creed, the Irish Minister for Agriculture, Food and the Marine, on 6 June to reiterate our concerns about the suspension of the Voisinage Agreement by Ireland. The Secretary of State further raised the issue with Minister Creed when they met on 13 June. Defra officials have also raised the matter with Irish counterparts on separate occasions.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-10-15T16:29:55.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973238/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973238/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-13","Fisheries: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, on which dates in 2018 (a) Ministers and (b) officials met with Irish counterparts to discuss the Voisinage Agreement.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","174646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973239","Department for International Trade","false","2018-10-15","<p>The Department for International Trade is a department for the whole of the UK and raises a number of issues with all counterparts that cover all four nations.</p><p><br>I have visited China four times this year and I have had discussions with several Chinese Ministries about removing barriers, increasing market access and helping businesses increase exports from across the whole of the UK. In August this year we successfully concluded an agreement with General Administration of Customs to enable UK dairy companies to export products containing dairy ingredients sourced from outside the UK. This will offer increased export flexibility to companies in Northern Ireland who wish to source ingredients from the Republic of Ireland. The agreement is estimated to be worth £240 million over 5 years to the UK. DIT China works closely with Northern Ireland’s Executive Office in the British Embassy Beijing.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2018-10-15T15:40:38.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973239/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973239/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-09-13","Exports: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussion he has had with his Chinese counterpart on the export of goods and services from Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","174725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973240","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-09","<p>The NHS Property Board has been established to provide leadership and strategic direction to the National Health Service on estates matters. As part of this, it will seek to ensure that estates issues are appropriately addressed in the long-term plan being developed by the NHS. The NHS Property Board and its constituent members are ensuring that local estates plans, supported by the strategic estates planning team, are grounded in local clinical strategies and adaptable to changes in demand. The Board is chaired by the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Health (Lord O’Shaughnessy). He has chaired six of the seven Board meetings that have taken place in 2018 but was unable to attend the July meeting due to parliamentary business. No other Ministers have attended any meetings. The Board also includes senior representatives from the Department of Health and Social Care and other key Government Departments, NHS England, NHS Improvement, NHS Property Services and Community Health Partnerships. Meetings of the NHS Property Board are held in closed session due to the confidential nature of items discussed.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","174756 ; 174757","2018-10-09T13:53:09.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973240/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/973240/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-13","Department of Health and Social Care: NHS Property Board","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many meetings of the NHS Property Board (a) he and (b) Ministers of his Department have attended in 2018 to date.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","174755"
